
CHAPTER XXXII.
THE RED LIGHT IN THE SKY.
My lady crushed the letter fiercely in her hand, and flung it from her into the flames.
"If he stood before me now, and I could kill him," she muttered in a strange, inward whisper,
     "I would do it—I would do it!" She snatched up the lamp and rushed into the adjoining room. She
     shut the door behind her. She could not endure any witness of her horrible despair—she could
     endure nothing, neither herself nor her surroundings.
